{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c6cf64b5-195a-4e41-9971-5496b64edf47","content":"**Use `dotnet workload update`.**\n\nAfter a .NET SDK update, your installed workloads (like `maui`) may lag behind the new SDK version. Here's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all your installed workloads, matching them to your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer versions to match a new SDK.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after updating, try `dotnet workload restore` in your project directory — it will install any workloads declared in your project's `global.json` or implied by your target frameworks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"35c146a5-a754-4dd8-9d56-d7c63722a65a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":271,"requestId":"9BDB:B0AF0:5E0C218:69428C0:69EC0DEC"},"id":"b0b3c1df-c3e6-4831-b3db-da85ba13ddea","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:42:28.016Z","parentId":"b8b8e459-c4ba-4dad-b1bf-98940b3e36d2"}
